5055","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/55055"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA two-year-old boy presents to the General Practice clinic with his parent for a routine check-up. He has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications. His parent reports that he occasionally experiences shortness of breath and has bluish discolouration of the skin. He also experiences constipation. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well. His pulse rate is 110/min, blood pressure 90/60 mmHg, respiratory rate 24/min, SpO2 94% on room air, and temperature 36.8\u00b0C. He has low muscle tone. His facial features include upward slanting eyes, a flat nasal bridge, and a protruding tongue. Cardiovascular examination reveals a pansystolic murmur. His ECG shows biventricular hypertrophy. Thyroid function tests show an elevated TSH of 12 mIU/L (0.5-5.0).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely underlying diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Down syndrome","Fragile X syndrome","Edwards syndrome","Cerebral palsy","Fetal alcohol syndrome"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe clinical features presented in this case are highly suggestive of \u003Cstrong\u003EDown syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E. Down syndrome is caused by trisomy 21, where there is an extra copy of a whole chromosome 21 or part of chromosome 21 (Translocation Down syndrome or Mosaic Down syndrome). The child demonstrates many classic features of Down syndrome, including characteristic facial features (upward slanting eyes, flat nasal bridge, protruding tongue), low muscle tone (hypotonia), and associated congenital heart defects.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe cardiac murmur and ECG findings suggesting biventricular hypertrophy are indicative of a congenital heart defect, likely an atrioventricular septal defect (AVSD), which is commonly associated with Down syndrome. The elevated TSH level indicates hypothyroidism, which is also more prevalent in individuals with Down syndrome and requires regular screening and management.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFragile X syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E is an X-linked disorder characterised by intellectual disability, a long face, large ears, and macroorchidism (enlarged testes). While it can cause developmental delays, it does not typically present with the characteristic facial features or cardiac defects seen in this child.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEdwards syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E (trisomy 18) causes severe intellectual disability, microcephaly, clenched fists with overlapping fingers, and rocker-bottom feet. Congenital heart defects are common in Edwards syndrome. However, most affected individuals do not survive beyond one year of age, making it less likely in this two-year-old child.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECerebral palsy\u003C/strong\u003E is a non-progressive disorder of movement and posture caused by abnormal brain development or injury. While hypotonia may be present in some forms of cerebral palsy, it does not cause the congenital heart defects or characteristic facial features observed in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFetal alcohol syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E is caused by prenatal alcohol exposure. Features include microcephaly, short palpebral fissures, smooth philtrum, and thin upper lip. Growth deficiency and intellectual disability are common in fetal alcohol syndrome. However, the characteristic facial features and cardiac defects typical of Down syndrome are not usually seen in fetal alcohol syndrome.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn conclusion, the combination of characteristic facial features, hypotonia, congenital heart defect, and hypothyroidism strongly supports the diagnosis of Down syndrome in this child. Regular medical follow-up, including cardiac and thyroid function monitoring, will be essential for optimal management.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The majority of patients with Down syndrome have an extra copy of chromosome 21.","Patients typically present with mild to moderate intellectual disability, growth retardation, and characteristic facial features including upward slanting eyes, flat nasal bridge, and protruding tongue.","Down syndrome is associated with an increased risk of congenital heart defects, particularly atrioventricular septal defects.","Hypothyroidism is more prevalent in individuals with Down syndrome and should be screened for regularly."],"references":["Akhtar F, Bokhari SRA. Down Syndrome. In: StatPearls [Internet]. [Updated 2022 Sep 6]. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK526016/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"40573"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12562"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"40573","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/40573"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-10-13T08:29:15+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-13T08:30:11+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5061"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"55055"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"2","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/2"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec0","name":"Cardiology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:21+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf6c","name":"Endocrinology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"ty